\ph[98%]{../tobago/8041_2206_1.jpg}{
Auction: 8041 - Trinidad & Tobago 
Lot: 2206 TOBAGO Early Letters and Handstamps 1787 (1 Aug.) entire letter to Edinburgh, marked "pr the Conte Dillon, Capt Barriman", rated "10" (deleted) and "1/5", showing straight-line "tabago" h.s. at left with light "col francaise/par/le havre" h.s. alongside and, London and arrival Bishop marks. The only recorded example of this straight-line handstamp, which was the only French postal marking used during the period of the French Occupation. B.P.A. Certificate (1989). Photo Estimate £ 11,000-15,000 Note: The French mail during this period was forwarded to Barbados. There is no record of British packets until Tobago was captured in 1793. provenance: R.H. Urwick, 1964 Ben Ramkissoon, 2006 Sold for £9,000
}

The first surviving letter in private hands to leave the Island after the British occupation is shown in Figure~\ref{britishoccupation}. The letter is dated 30 May 1793 and is addressed to London. The letter is from Major Gordon of the 60th Foot who lead the assault on Fort Castries and accepted the surrender of the French. The contents include "There was a Great Ball given this evening to General Cuyler in honour of his conquest of Tobago.", "....the night which I stormed the Fort at Tobago." and" At present it is uncertain whether I shall return to be Military Governor of Tobago or command the Light Troops on the Expedition". A historically important letter and the earliest recorded following the British capture of Tobago. Photo Estimate £ 1,200-1,500 Note: Major-General Cornelius Cuyler and Squadron Leader Vice-Admiral John Laforey sailed for Tobago (under French control since 2 July 1781) and landed their troops at Great Courland Bay on 14 April. Major Gordon lead the asault on Fort castries. Losses were light (18 killed on both sides). General Cuyler was seriously wounded and, as a result, Major Gordon took command and accepted the surrender from the French Governor Laroque de Monteil on 14 April 1793.

